    <title>Combined summary - BIP 151 use of HMAC_SHA512</title>
    <updated>2023-06-11T18:55:04.293299+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2016-June/012827.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The context covers various topics related to cryptography and encryption protocols in the Bitcoin development community. One of the discussions revolves around the use of SHA512 for encryption key generation using HMAC_SHA512 hash, with a suggestion to use HMAC_SHA256 hash instead. Another debate is about the introduction of SHA512_HMAC and its necessity, with concerns raised about its security compared to SHA256. The importance of using well-studied open standards over custom constructions in cryptography is emphasized, with a recommendation to read the paper on HKDF.In addition, there is a discussion about the inclusion of cipher-type in the symmetric cipher key to avoid weak-cipher attacks. There are also debates about using HMAC instead of SHA256 for message authentication codes (MACs), with concerns raised about the length extension property of SHA256. Finally, there is a discussion about the potential use of SHA3 as an alternative to SHA512, although it is explained that the security of the symmetric cipher key mainly depends on the PRNG and ECDH scheme.Zooko Wilcox recommends using well-studied open standards like HMAC-based Extract-and-Expand Key Derivation Function (HKDF) instead of reinventing them, as they are widely understood and reduce the risk of errors. He suggests reading a paper about HKDF to understand its design decisions. Arthur Chen agrees with Wilcox's recommendation and emphasizes the importance of using open standards in cryptography.There were debates about using SHA512_HMAC instead of SHA256_HMAC, but no clear pros or cons were identified. One conversation snippet highlights the importance of following well-studied open standards in cryptocurrency rather than opting for custom constructions. Another conversation discusses BIP151, which utilizes ECDH in conjunction with ChaCha20-Poly1305 for encryption.Finally, there was a debate about whether to use HKDF or a single SHA512_HMAC operation, but the implications of using HKDF over HMAC_SHA512 are still being evaluated. Overall, it is recommended to use standard algorithms to reduce the risk of errors, even if there may be a slight cost involved.</summary>
